title: For Trade:  M1 Garand
postcontent:
Up for grabs is my "made in America" M1 Garand! 

My serial number was produced in April 1939. Overwhelming odds are that this rifle saw active duty in WWII due to the high demand in those early years. Think about it... my serial number is 1**40 and troops were not fully issued until serial number 400,000+

Here is the reason it is stamped CAI:

1. America left a lot of firearms in foreign countries after WWII.
2. The gun control act of 1968 gave the ATF power to regulate imports.
3. ATF then started requiring all firearms entering America to be stamped by the importer. This included American arms "returning' to our country.
4. So your serial number and "CAI" stamp simply means that the rifle left the country prior to 1968 and returned after that. A virtual guarantee that it saw active duty in at least one and possibly several wars.



I have 5 upper end contractor clips, and 5 mil spec 8rnd clips. I have recently added a Korean War Issue GI web sling to it as well.

and 80 or so .30-06 rounds from various manufacturers. I also have 60-80 empty re-loadable brass cases.

title: For Sale:  Swiss K31 (with dies, brass, ammo, and name-tag!)
postcontent:
The K31 is known for excellent accuracy and fine quality. It's a Swiss product, after all!


                                             ***Note on ammo***
GP11 surplus ammo is not at all hard to find, and is match-grade in terms of accuracy. Usually you can buy it by the case for $0.60 per round online, or in most good gun shops for $0.75 per round. 


                                               ***General Info***
As mentioned in the title, I will be including a set of Lee reloading dies, a bag of NORMA brass (yeah, the good stuff. Trimmed and ready to go!), a partial box (18rds) of premium norma hunting ammo, and a bag of 100 Hornady 150gr .308 bullets (that's right, the 7.5x55 Swiss uses the same .308/7.62 projectiles that your 308Win, 30-06, etc. all use). If you need primers, I have one last box of 100 large rifle primers that you can have for a couple bucks if you need 'em.


                                              ***Rifle Details***
The rifle is in excellent condition. The stock has its knicks and scratches as is common for these rifles, but the bluing underneath the wood is *PERFECT* and the receiver metal looks great with just a little bit of wear. Also, all the numbers on this rifle match including the magazine, stock, and bolt. In addition, the rifle also has the original owner's name-tag with address on it. I looked him up and it seems his family is still around at that location (some folks have been able to contact the original owners of these things and have gotten pictures back of the soldier with the rifle. Pretty cool!). Also, it is possible to mount a scope to these rifles without drilling into the receiver! A clamp-on mount is made by swiss products and they are very popular and affordable. 

Anyway, I'm selling this to fund a new project, not because it is a bad rifle. I will be anywhere from Maple Valley to Everett tomorrow, so give me a call or text and I will probably be able to meet up with you at some point to make the sale. I'd really like to sell this tomorrow as I will be out-and-about!

If you have a trade offer, I may be interested but not if it is for something that isn't a firearm. 


                                            ***Cost Breakdown***
I think given the condition of the rifle, and the fact I will be including the reloading stuff, that $400 is fair. If you break it down that's $330 for the rifle, $25 for the dies, $22 for the bullets, and $23 for the ammo. If I sell the rifle, I need to get rid of at least the ammo at the same time as I have no other rifles in this caliber, and I can just ebay the dies. So for a minimum price, just the rifle and ammo, would be $353. 

**NOTE**: If you would like to buy it, but don't think my price is fair, or don't want the reloading stuff, please just make me an offer and I will let you know ASAP. There's no harm in asking me, worst I can say is no!



                       *****My phone number is 206-371-three-eight-6-6*****

title: For Sale/Trade:  Taurus PT709 Slim 9mm
postcontent:
This is a lightly used Taurus PT709 that comes with original box and two 7 round magazines. The PT709 is a single stack, 7+1 round 9mm semi-automatic pistol.  It is just over six inches long (6.24″), four and a half inches high (4.52″), and an amazing one inch (1.04″) wide.  It has a steel slide with a polymer frame which adds up to a diminutive nineteen ounces. 

The PT709 is a striker-fired weapon with an interesting single-action/double action capability.  When a round is chambered, the trigger pull is always about 5-6 lbs in single action mode.  However, if a round fails to fire, the PT709 allows a second pull of the trigger in double-action mode (about 6-7lbs) without racking the slide.  It offers a true double-strike capability on a dud round without cycling the slide.  The PT709 has a nicely positioned thumb safety and a trigger safety like that of a Glock which allows for it to be safely carried with a round in the chamber.  It also has a firing pin block to prevent the weapon from firing unless the trigger safety has been pressed.  I like that safety redundancy in a CCW.

Besides the trigger safety there are other Glock-like features of the PT709 Slim, namely the way it’s disassembled.  Rather than removing a pin to free the slide, the 709 has a set of take-down latches on either side which free the slide.  A slide-lock release is just ahead of the thumb safety on the frame and the magazine release is nicely placed on the grip and easy to access. 

Great gun for a great price. ALL NC LAWS APPLY. Buyer must produce a NC ID, Pistol Permit or Concealed Carry Permit and sign a bill of sale.
